Cardio Good Fitness¶

Background:¶

Cardio Good Fitness, a retail store wants to build a customer profile for treadmill products in its offering. There is a set of data that has been collected from the customers of the retail store. The ask is to extracting insights from data that will assist in targeting new customers

Objective:¶

  1. Build up a customer profile for different products of Cardio Good Fitness.
  2. Suggest insights and recommendations that will help the company in targeting new customers.

Questions:¶

  • What are the different factors that influence customers towards a particular product offering?
  • What are the key recommendations, to get new customers?

Data Description:¶

  1. Product - the model no. of the treadmill
  2. Age - in no of years, of the customer
  3. Gender - of the customer
  4. Education - in no. of years, of the customer
  5. Marital Status - of the customer
  6. Usage - Avg. # times the customer wants to use the treadmill every week
  7. Fitness - Self rated fitness score of the customer (5 - very fit, 1 - very unfit)
  8. Income - of the customer
  9. Miles- expected to run

Numerical values exploration¶

In [1097]:
# import the library for labelling
import matplotlib.patheffects as path_effects

def add_median_labels(ax):
    lines = ax.get_lines()
    # determine number of lines per box (this varies with/without fliers)
    boxes = [c for c in ax.get_children() if type(c).__name__ == 'PathPatch']
    lines_per_box = int(len(lines) / len(boxes))
    # iterate over median lines
    for median in lines[4:len(lines):lines_per_box]:
        # display median value at center of median line
        x, y = (data.mean() for data in median.get_data())
        # choose value depending on horizontal or vertical plot orientation
        value = x if (median.get_xdata()[1]-median.get_xdata()[0]) == 0 else y
        text = ax.text(x, y, f'{value:.1f}', ha='center', va='center',
                       fontweight='bold', color='white', bbox=dict(facecolor='black'),size=15)
        # create median-colored border around white text for contrast
        text.set_path_effects([
            path_effects.Stroke(linewidth=3, foreground=median.get_color()),
            path_effects.Normal(),
        ])
In [1098]:
def box_and_histogram(column,  figsize=(10,10), bins = None):
    """ Boxplot and histogram together, with median labels on boxplot
    df_series: dataframe column
    figsize: size of fig (default (9,8))
    bins: number of bins (default None / auto)
    color of mean is green and median is black
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(nrows = 2, # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
                                           sharex = True, # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
                                           gridspec_kw = {"height_ratios": (.25, .75)}, 
                                           figsize = figsize 
                                            ) # creating the 2 subplots
    box_plot = sns.boxplot(column, ax=ax_box2,showmeans=True, color='red')
    add_median_labels(box_plot.axes)
 

    sns.distplot(column, kde=F, bins=bins) if bins else sns.distplot(column, kde=False, ) # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(np.mean(column), color='g', linestyle='--') # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(np.median(column), color='black', linestyle='-') # Add median to the histogram

# Function to create barplots that indicate percentage for each category.
def barplot_with_percent(plot, df_series):
    '''
    plot
    df_series: dataframe column
    '''
    
    total = len(df_series) # length of the column
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = '{:.1f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total) # percentage of each class of the category
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.05 # width of the plot
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()           # hieght of the plot
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x, y), size = 12) # annotate the percantage

Correlation¶
In [1109]:
# Check for correlation among numerical variables
num_var = ['Age','Education','Usage','Fitness','Income', 'Miles']

corr = df[num_var].corr()
In [1110]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
# plot the heatmap
sns.heatmap(corr, annot=True,cmap='coolwarm',
        fmt=".1f",
        xticklabels=corr.columns,
        yticklabels=corr.columns);

Observations

  • Usage and Miles, Miles and Fitness are corelated. 
         The more the usage the more Miles are run.
     As more miles are run , the user is at a higher Fitness level.
  • Understandably, Fitness and Usage have a correlation
  • Important to note that correlation does not imply causation.
  • There does not seem to be a strong relationship between Usage and Age.

Conclusion and Recommendations¶
Conclusion¶
Dataset of 180 observation was analysed. This data contained the usage characteristics of the customer across three different products. Product TM195 had the most observations. The key feature will be usage per week. Also related are Fitness level and miles expected to run per week as these two feature (Fitness level and miles per week) will influence the usage.


We can summarize that:


    

  1. Most customers have TM195 product.
    2. 

  2. There are more male customer than female customers.
    3. 

  3. There are more customers who are with Marital Status of Partnered. 
    4. 

  4. Customers between 24 to 33 are more likely to use the product
    5. 

  5. TM195 & TM498, have a similar customer profile regarding usage level, Age, income and miles run per week
